Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels—For most of the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in curbing powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at zero levels, while also conducting multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchase operations.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have all followed the Federal Reserve's example, each implementing their own versions of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But inflation has not achieved a reasonable rise anywhere.
Although these countries are all fighting against deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — and economic performances — are diverging.
The growth in the US and the UK is now strong enough to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the Eurozone and Japan are stepping up QE, pushing long-term policy interest rates further into negative territory.
What is the reason for this difference?
The short answer is debt.
For decades, the US and the UK have had current account deficits, making them debtor nations, while the Eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses, making them creditor nations.
Negative interest rates benefit debtor nations but harm creditor nations. Therefore, the negative interest rates introduced after the global economic crisis stimulated recovery in the US and the UK, but had little effect on the Eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, most creditor nations in the world — countries with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland — have experienced negative interest rates, not only on long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also on medium-term bonds.
This is definitely not a good thing.
Although low interest rates have yielded limited results, central banks in these economies continue to adhere to this policy.
If you suggest that QE or lowering interest rates cannot bring benefits to the economy, they will change the subject and argue against the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — on the surface, this seems unassailable.
But in reality, it is full of loopholes.
Basic economics courses mention this peculiar phenomenon called the "backward-bending supply curve of savings": in certain environments, lowering interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because lower interest rates reduce the income of savers, they will cut back on spending, especially if they are saving for retirement.
None of this is meant to negate the general rule — which forms the basis of modern monetary policy — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other expenditures.
However, the impact varies due to differences in the debt situations of the economies.
In a closed economy, every creditor has a debtor, so whatever the creditors lose due to extremely low interest rates, the debtors should benefit.
But in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors naturally outnumber debtors.
The situation is exactly the opposite for a country with a large amount of foreign debt.
Therefore, the effects of monetary policy with interest rate floors differ between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important, as foreign asset positions were often small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
However, nowadays, the foreign asset positions of major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, partly due to the leverage that led to the 2007–2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, leverage continues to increase at the national level.
Although current account imbalances have eased somewhat since the beginning of the financial crisis, they have not reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, leading to a divergence from deficit economies.
Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, had large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, making them the main exceptions to the differentiation in foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, world oil prices have crashed, reversing the wealth trends of these countries.
Their export earnings have sharply declined —— many countries losing half —— forcing them to run deficits, relying on the large sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodity boom period.
Now, a sharp reduction in spending has become inevitable.
Industrialized economies face completely different challenges.
Their problem —— in a way, a luxury problem —— is to ensure that consumers spend the windfall gained from the drop in import prices.
But in creditor nations, negative interest rates seem to be failing to advance this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence also exists within the Eurozone.
Although as a whole, the Eurozone is a creditor economy, there are also debtor countries within it.
Debtor economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debts.
However, traditional debtor countries have such high current account surpluses that the asymmetry between debtor and creditor countries continues to increase.
Most noteworthy is that since the outbreak of the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that the surplus accumulated by Germany during this period has exceeded the total historical surplus before.
Following the current trend, Germany's creditor position may increase from 60% of GDP to 100%.
Central bank governors should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
However, central bank governors seem to lack patience, greatly troubled by low inflation, despite the output gap gradually closing, with the US and Japan achieving full employment.
Central bank governors of debtor nations must stop manipulating the economy with more monetary easing that may be detrimental to production.
On the contrary, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of the falling oil prices to disappear.
Recently, ECB President Draghi admitted that the current monetary policy framework may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more of the same old remedy is not the solution.
